h3. Issue Summary
It seems that the Decisions Report macro changes the order of the information randomly every time you refresh the page or navigate to a different page.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page;
# Add the decision report macro
** Set the macro to get pages from the same space you are creating the page and to get pages that contain the label {{decision-report}};
# Publish the page;
# Do the following to create three different pages:
** Create a page;
** Add a Decision macro and insert any text content in the macro;
** Publish the page;
** Add the label {{decision-report}};
# Go to the first page we created (the report one);
# Note how the Decision report is sorted;
# Refresh the page.

h3. Expected Results
After refreshing the page or either navigating to other pages then coming back to the report page, the list of decisions and their pages should be in the same order.

h3. Actual Results
The order of the information pulled in the report macro changes all the time.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary
Creating JIRA issues from a Confluence page that has a table allows us to create multiple JIRA issues at once, saving us a lot of time.
Apparently, when the issues we are creating are placed within an EPIC one, not all the issues we requested get created.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
*On JIRA*
# Go to any of your Software projects;
# Create an EPIC issue;
# Take note of its number.

*On Confluence*:
# Create a page;
# Insert the JIRA issue macro, and search for the EPIC you created before;
# Insert a table with 100 rows;
# In the first column, name the header and add random text in each of the cells (you can add numbers from 1 to 100, to make it easier to see the issue happening);
# Publish the page;
# From the first cell, highlight its text and select the *Create Issue* option;
# From the dialog box, click on "_Create multiple issues from table_";
# Leave things as they are and hit the *Create* button;
# After it is done, access the EPIC on JIRA.

h3. Expected Results
All the 100 tickets were successfully created under the EPIC.

h3. Actual Results
Only part of the issues is created under the EPIC (from around 25 to 50).

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

When updating a draft using the REST API (PUT /wiki/rest/api/content/\{id\}?status=draft), the draft's body.storage will be updated but those changes won't take effect on the editor.

When the page is edited through the UI, the old contents are shown.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page and copy its ID
 # Perform the following request (replace the PAGE_ID and the INSTACE_URL)
{code:js}
fetch("https://INSTACE_URL/wiki/rest/api/content/450953226?status=draft", {
    "headers": {
        "content-type": "application/json",
    },
    "body": "{\"version\":{\"number\":1},\"type\":\"page\",\"status\":\"draft\",\"title\":\"Page title - updated through API\",\"body\":{\"storage\": {\"value\": \"<p>Test draft</p>\",\"representation\": \"storage\"}}}",
    "method": "PUT",
}){code}

 # Edit the page through the UI

h3. Expected Results

The draft should contain "Test draft"
h3. Actual Results

The draft still shows the old contents
h3. Workaround

Currently, the only available workaround is to force the draft to refresh through the following request after the update:
{code:js}
fetch("https://INSTANCE_URL/wiki/rest/synchrony/1.0/content/PAGE_ID/recovery?behind=SYNCHRONY", {
  "headers": {
    "accept": "*/*",
  },
  "body": null,
  "method": "PUT"
});{code}

h3. Issue Summary

Back in a day, when we were creating pages in a space that already have a page with the same title, Confluence would pop-up us a message clarifying this. 
 Nowadays, it seems it is only throwing a general error message.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page and name is as "_Test Page_";
 # Publish it;
 # Create a new page and name it as "_Test Page_";
 # Try to publish it.

h3. Expected Results

An error message saying that a page with that title already exists will be shown.
h3. Actual Results

A generic message is shown on the screen saying:
 _*Your work is safe, but there's an issue.*_
 _Refresh the page, and click Publish again_
 _!image-2021-01-25-17-58-02-047.png|width=420,height=84!_

 

*Identifying the scenario you are dealing with*
 # Open the browser developer console, and click over the *Network* tab;
 # After that, hit the Publish button again;
 # A red text will appear, click there;
 # Open the Response tab;
 # Locate this piece of text: {{A page with this title already exists}}

!Identifyingtheissue.gif|width=924,height=458!

In case you located it, follow the below workaround. 
 In case you didn't, raise a new [support ticket|https://support.atlassian.com/contact/] to us mentioning this bug request, the page you are facing this issue, and the data access approved in the ticket.
h3. Workaround

After identifying the this is the case, change the page's title and then publish it.

h3. Issue Summary

Certain terms seem to be reserved on Confluence. The "_jQuery_" is one of them: when we add a header name with this term, our pages do not behave well.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a new page;
 # Add a title to it;
 # Chose any header style and type “_jQuery_” in it;
 # Publish the page;
 # Refresh it.

h3. Expected Results

The page is refreshed with no issues.
h3. Actual Results

The page breaks with a random error code, like the message below:
!image-2021-01-18-09-55-02-433.png!

*Notes*:
 * This behavior is presented with all the header options on Confluence;
 * Apparently, after publishing the page the error doesn't come up at the first moment, but eventually when the browser needs to refresh the cached session, then it will happen without the need to force the browser refresh;
 * It also happens on already published pages;
 * Confluence seems to read "_jQuery_" as an HTML object when it is added to a header, as it names the header ID with the same title as the header text:
{code:html}
<h1 id="jQuery" data-renderer-start-pos="1">jQuery </h1>{code}

 * Once the page is refreshed, then Confluence will try to get this object, but as it is not about jQuery itself, it throws an error in the backend (also possible to see it in the browser console):
{code:java}
TypeError: Object(...) is not a function{code}

h3. Workaround

Either remove the header format or add more text to the header (instead of "_jQuery_", for example, you can add "_The jQuery_". You can do this from your browser by accessing the editing mode of this page directly from the URL: {{https://<SITENAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/<SPACEKEY>/pages/edit-v2/<CONTENTID>}}

h3. Issue Summary

[Content Label API|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-content-labels/#api-api-content-id-label-post] returns 500 status code (Server Error) instead of 4xx if we pass invalid label names i.e. label name containing invalid characters (':', ';', ',', '.', ' ', '?', '&', '[', ']', '(', ')', '#', '^', '*', '@', '!', '<', '>') or label name size is too long or if we pass more than 20 labels at a time or if user doesn't have EDIT permission to confluence page.

 

Another problem with the API is its response error messages, some of the error messages contain the label name in args param which had an issue, but some do not. For example, if we pass 2 labels in the payload (which this API allows), one with invalid characters and another with a label name too long (more than 255 characters), then the response is something like below:

{color:#0747a6}*Payload:*{color}

 
{code:java}
[  
  {    
    "prefix": "global",
    "name": "test-*"  
  },  
  { 
    "prefix": "global",
    "name": ""  
  }
]{code}
*{color:#0747a6}Response:{color}*
{    
  "statusCode": 500,    
  "message": "com.atlassian.confluence.core.service.NotValidException: [ValidationError [messageKey=label.contains.invalid.chars, args=[global:test-*,  , !, #, &, (, ), *, ,, ., :, ;, <, >, ?, @, [, ], ^]], ValidationError [messageKey=label.name.is.too.long, args=[255]]]"
}
 

It would be great if this can be made consistent by adding the label names to the error message in a consumable format.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Call [Content Label API|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-content-labels/#api-api-content-id-label-post] (/wiki/rest/api/content/\{id}/label) with a payload

{code:java}
[  
  {
    "prefix": "global",    
    "name": "test-*"  
  },  
  {    
    "prefix": "global",
    "name": "test"  
  }
]
{code}
     2. Remove edit permission of user from confluence page and call [Content Label API|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/api-group-content-labels/#api-api-content-id-label-post] (/wiki/rest/api/content/\{id}/label) with a payload
{code:java}
[ 
  { 
    "prefix":"global", 
    "name":"test-1" 
  }, 
  { "prefix":"global",
    "name":"test" 
  } 
]
{code}
h3. Expected Results

Response status code must be 4xx with a proper error message.
h3. Actual Results

The below responses are thrown for different requests
{noformat}
{    
  "statusCode": 500,    
  "message": "com.atlassian.confluence.core.service.NotValidException: [ValidationError [messageKey=label.contains.invalid.chars, args=[global:test-*,  , !, #, &, (, ), *, ,, ., :, ;, <, >, ?, @, [, ], ^]]]"
}
{noformat}
{code:java}
{
    "statusCode": 500,
    "message": "com.atlassian.confluence.core.service.NotValidException: [ValidationError [messageKey=only.personal.labels.permitted, args=[]], ValidationError [messageKey=only.personal.labels.permitted, args=[]]]"
}{code}
h3. Workaround

Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available
